[FULL TEXT ANALYSIS BELOW]
nature medicine
https://doi.org/10.1038/s41591-024-03013-7
News & views
Cardiometabolic diseases
What the SELECT trial of semaglutide 
means for clinicians
Naveed Sattar, Matthew M. Y. Lee & Darren K. McGuire
Accumulating data support the systemic 
benefits of semaglutide (and potentially 
other GLP-1RA-based therapies) in people 
with obesity, meaning that cardiologists 
and other clinicians must become familiar 
with prescribing them — particularly once 
market competition makes these drugs more 
accessible.
The SELECT trial — which evaluated semaglutide in individuals with obe-
sity and pre-existing atherosclerotic cardiovascular disease (but with-
out diabetes) — was the first outcome trial of a glucagon-like peptide-1 
receptor agonist (GLP-1RA) in such a population, and its results were 
eagerly awaited. The primary outcome, reported in 2023, showed a 20% 
reduction in major cardiovascular outcomes with high-dose subcuta-
neous semaglutide (2.4 mg once a week) in the trial population1. The 
results of SELECT also showed that semaglutide nominally reduced 
all-cause mortality and incident heart failure, although the hierarchical 
testing scheme for secondary outcomes meant that it was not tested 
for superiority in regard to these conditions1. Even so, the accumulated 
data led the US Food and Drug Administration (FDA) to approve a new 
indication for high-dose semaglutide — that is, to reduce cardiovascular 
risk in adults with obesity — making it the first medication licensed for 
obesity to get such an indication in the USA.
Now, two studies in this issue of Nature Medicine present results 
from pre-specified analyses of the SELECT trial, which further our 
understanding of how semaglutide works and of its wider impacts. 
Ryan et al.2 show that semaglutide provides durable (over 4 years) and 
meaningful weight loss across key demographic characteristics, while 
the results of Colhoun et al.3 suggest that semaglutide slows kidney 
function decline and dampens albuminuria (both of which are associ-
ated with obesity), as compared with placebo.
Several aspects of these two new papers, on top of the primary 
report of the SELECT trial results1, are worth highlighting. First, 
although the extent to which semaglutide-induced weight loss influ-
enced the primary cardiovascular outcome is not easily determined, 
the durability of weight loss reported by Ryan et al.2, without attenu-
ation over time, provides convincing evidence that the weight loss 
benefit of semaglutide is likely to be sustainable for several years — pro-
vided that individuals continue to take the medication. Furthermore, 
the finding of average placebo-corrected weight losses of 7.3–11.1% 
across age, sex, race and baseline body mass index (BMI) subgroups is 
noteworthy. These findings are important because higher BMI seems 
to be the strongest contributor to the development of multimorbidity4 
(at least on the basis of data from high-income countries), and it is likely 
that excess adiposity over long periods accentuates damage to many 
tissues — such that only sustained weight loss will slow the development 
of several chronic conditions. Furthermore, results from randomized 
trials show that weight loss magnitudes similar to that seen in SELECT 
can rapidly affect the incidence or remission of certain chronic diseases 
(such as type 2 diabetes5) and that symptoms of other obesity-linked 
conditions (such as heart failure with preserved ejection fraction) can 
be meaningfully improved within a year6.
In terms of kidney protection, the results presented by Colhoun 
et al.3 are not definitive; the pre-specified composite endpoint was 
driven primarily by changes in albuminuria and estimated glomer-
ular filtration rate (eGFR) declines rather than ‘harder’ outcomes. 
Nevertheless, they are consistent with evidence from multiple other 
sources. GLP-1RAs, as a drug class, may protect against chronic kidney 
disease (CKD) outcomes in persons with type 2 diabetes, according 
to previous meta-analyses7. The FLOW trial8, due to report in 2024, 
will extend these results. Bariatric surgery has also been associated 
with the slowing of decline in kidney function and progression to 
end-stage kidney disease9. Furthermore, as now noted by Colhoun 
et al.3, an early, transient decline in eGFR with semaglutide matches 
what is seen with sodium–glucose co-transporter 2 (SGLT2) inhibi-
tor10 treatment. These findings may represent an early ‘hemody-
namic correction’ to volume overload in turn linked to early diuresis 
which, along with a decline in blood pressure, de-stresses the kid-
neys. Further trials of high-dose semaglutide in individuals with 
CKD and obesity but without diabetes are now required to prove 
a definitive protective action against CKD. Such trials could also 
show whether such CKD benefits are additive to those from SGLT2 
inhibitor treatment.
