The clinical implications of all the SELECT findings so far (and 
to come) will need to be considered carefully. In some countries 
(such as Germany), because of strict legislation, weight-loss and 
appetite-suppressant medications are not covered by the country’s 
public health insurance program — in part because of high costs. How-
ever, these medications are likely to be licensed soon for cardiovascular 
protection, and thus in certain countries cardiologists may be among 
the first groups able to prescribe them. Cardiologists therefore need 
to become familiar with prescribing this class of medications11; yet so 
far, only a minority are doing so, with barriers including the need for 
injections and multiple dose up-titrations, plus the need to provide 
advice to set patient expectations and to mitigate against gastrointes-
tinal side effects. Of note, the lower incidence of serious adverse events 
with semaglutide compared to placebo (consistent across baseline 
BMI categories) should reassure prescribing clinicians. Improvements 
in self-rated health1 also hint at wider benefits of semaglutide, whose 
appetite suppression effect has multiple systemic downstream benefits 
(Fig. 1), further justifying its provision by health systems. Ultimately, 
each country will need to navigate the most efficient and cost-effective 
way to prescribe these medications, a process that could be facilitated 
by the development of digital tools.
Taking a wider view, as more evidence accrues to show disease- 
modifying effects of anti-obesity medicines in other disease areas, it 
is likely that many different specialties will need to become familiar 
with prescribing these medicines in future. Hopefully, over the next 
few years, other anti-obesity medications will replicate and extend the 
benefits seen in SELECT, so that a greater range of treatment options 
become available — leading to lower costs as competitive marketing 
kicks in. This is crucial as the number of people now living with obesity 
and related comorbidities, and who therefore could meaningfully 
benefit from such medications, is substantial; currently, many health 
systems can only afford to treat a limited number of such individuals.
Looking to the future, it will be crucial to tackle multimorbidity 
